[5] Regional updates: ProMED-SoAs
[A] Bangladesh
Date: Fri 11 Jun 2021 02:57 BST
Source: The Daily Star [edited]
https://www.thedailystar.net/frontpage/news/health-crisis-deepens-border-districts-2108649


Many hospitals in the districts along the border are at full capacity as they are grappling with an increasing number of COVID-19 patients.

There is hardly any bed for new COVID-19 patients in at least 5 hospitals in Satkhira, Khulna, Natore, Rajshahi, and Panchagarh. These hospitals have been turning away patients for the past few days.

Besides, the number of daily new cases has increased across the country. For the 24 hours preceding 8:00 am yesterday [10 Jun 2021], the Directorate General of Health Services [DGHS] reported 2576 new cases, the highest daily cases since 28 Apr 2021. The DGHS said 40 people died in the same period, which was 36 the previous day.

The positivity rate has also gone up. It was 13.25 yesterday [10 Jun 2021] from 12.33 the day before.

With the new cases, the total number of active COVID-19 cases rose to around 50 000. Of them, 3200 were being treated at hospitals, according to a press release from the DGHS.

The official death toll in the country has reached 12 989 and the death rate stood at 1.58%. Of those who were reported dead yesterday [10 Jun 2021], the highest -- 12 -- were in Chattogram division, followed by 8 each in Dhaka and Rajshahi, and 6 in Khulna, 4 in Rangpur, and 2 in Sylhet.

With no beds available, the authorities of Khulna Medical College Hospital (KMCH) stopped admitting patients in its 100-bed COVID-19 unit, reported our correspondent in the city. As of yesterday afternoon [10 Jun 2021], 126 patients were admitted there.

"We're at capacity. There is no empty bed and that's why we stopped taking in new patients," said Resident Medical Officer Suhash Ranjan Halder of the COVID-19 unit at KMCH. "Doctors and nurses are always struggling to handle the rush of critical patients. If we admit any more patients, we won't be able to properly treat the critical ones," he said.

Our correspondent from Natore reported that the district hospital was in a similar situation. Besides, the hospital does not have a central oxygen supply system to provide high flow oxygen to patients, who have been gasping for oxygen. Yesterday afternoon [10 Jun 2021], there were 43 COVID-19 patients against 30 beds in this hospital, which was struggling with an inadequate number of physicians and technicians, said Assistant Director Paritosh Kumar.

Our correspondent from Chapainawabganj reported that the 250-bed district hospital had 55 COVID-19 patients admitted yesterday afternoon [10 Jun 2021] against its capacity to treat 50. As the number of patients was increasing, the hospital authorities were thinking about raising the bed number to 70, said Dr Ahnaf Shahriar, focal person of the COVID-19 unit of the hospital.

Our Thakurgaon correspondent reported the district hospital, with a 50-bed COVID-19 unit, cannot provide ventilator support to critical patients. "We have a limited capacity to treat patients. So we are advising patients to follow our treatment protocols at home," Dr Rokibul Alam, resident medical officer at the hospital, told the Daily Star yesterday [10 Jun 2021].

Meanwhile, the administrations of Khulna, Chapainawabganj, Satkhira, Bagerhat, and Noakhali districts continued enforcing strict restrictions on movement to curb the virus transmission.

--
