Maldives: 69 536 / 191 / 348
Bhutan: 1769 / 1 / 1

Over the last 7 days, 700 473, 14 415, 10149, 24 751, and 3020 COVID-19 cases were detected in India, Bangladesh, Pakistan, Nepal, and the Maldives, respectively, compared with 1 026 645, 10 995, 17 286, 34 680, and 5573 in the preceding 7 days, revealing a sharp decreasing trend in India, Pakistan, Nepal, and the Maldives, but a steady upward trend in Bangladesh. In Sri Lanka, a stable trend was seen over the last 7 days after growing new cases sustainably in the previous 4 weeks or so. The total deaths in Sri Lanka attributed to the disease have just passed the landmark of 2000.

The daily case-positivity in several border districts in Bangladesh is currently very high, and recent sequence data of the virus from 50 samples collected in the country revealed the predominance of delta variant (previously called B.1.617.2), a variant of concern (see archive no. 20210605.8424801), which is more transmissible than the alpha variant. Only time will say whether the steady and sustainable growth in new cases, as being observed over the last 2 weeks, would turn into a significant 3rd wave of the disease in the country.

On Thursday 10 Jun 2021, India registered 6148 deaths attributed to COVID-19, the highest single-day count from the country. This surprisingly high count was the result of adding the previously uncounted 3951 deaths from Bihar state. It is not clear whether other backlogs of deaths from other states remain to be counted, amending the official number of COVID-19 deaths reported so far.

To compare the situation in South Asian countries above with previous disease data, ProMED readers are referred to the ProMED-SoAs archives below:

